12/18/2025

FTC privacy/security guidance review
FTC privacy and security hub:
https://www.ftc.gov/business-guidance/privacy-security?utm_source=chatgpt.com

Reviewed FTC guidance emphasizing that organizations must follow the privacy promises they make to users (i.e., “say what you do, and do what you say”).

Logged key principle: privacy statements become commitments—misstatements can create enforcement risk.

Health Breach Notification Rule page:
https://www.ftc.gov/enforcement/rules/rulemaking-regulatory-reform-proceedings/health-breach-notification-rule

Reviewed HBN Rule overview and noted relevance primarily to health apps / health data and certain related services.

Captured the general takeaway: breach-related duties depend on the type of data and whether it qualifies as covered health information under FTC scope.

FTC Consumer Privacy guidance:
https://www.ftc.gov/business-guidance/privacy-security/consumer-privacy

Reviewed FTC guidance reinforcing:

honoring privacy policies and user disclosures

aligning representations with actual practices

understanding FTC Act enforcement themes (deception/unfairness)

heightened sensitivity around health-related data and breach-related expectations

12/20/2025
✅ Non-Recording Visualization Disclosure (Original / Ready to Use)

Non-Recording Visualization Notice
This software uses your device microphone only to generate real-time visual output inside your browser.

No audio is recorded

No audio is stored or saved

No audio or derived data is transmitted off-device

No sharing, uploading, or retention occurs

Audio signals are processed temporarily in-memory for visualization and then discarded immediately

This visualization does not:

create recordings or audio files

store frequency “snapshots” linked to a user or session

send audio to servers or third parties

associate microphone input with identity

Granting microphone permission enables live visual analysis only, not surveillance or monitoring.

Recommended placement locations:

near the microphone permission UI

inside a Privacy / Compliance section

in your compliance log as a standing disclosure

in a privacy.html page or COMPLIANCE.md

Suggested additional sentence:
“This software is not intended to intercept, monitor, or surveil audio and does not function as a recording tool.”

Compliance note:
Always confirm final claims against actual statute language and consult counsel for high-stakes interpretations.

FTC resource: App Developers – Start with Security
https://www.ftc.gov/business-guidance/resources/app-developers-start-security

Key takeaways logged:

Security expectations vary by app, but “reasonable security” is the baseline

Third-party SDKs/libraries can introduce privacy and security gaps

App distribution increases scrutiny for privacy/security representations

Devices can be lost/stolen; secure storage and minimize retained data

Assign ownership for security tasks (even if it’s just you)

Collect only what you need; retain only as long as needed

Understand platform differences and built-in security features

Protect usernames/passwords and any authentication mechanisms
